1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:05,700
KeyError is one of the other types of look up errors in the Python exception hierarchy.

2

00:00:05,700  -->  00:00:07,600
To understand the KeyError,

3

00:00:07,600  -->  00:00:11,320
imagine a guest asks about a particular food item like a churro,

4

00:00:11,320  -->  00:00:13,380
but you look up the wrong food stall.

5

00:00:13,380  -->  00:00:18,260
Python raises a KeyError when you try to access a dictionary key that doesn't exist.

6

00:00:18,260  -->  00:00:20,755
Let's see an example of this in action.

7

00:00:20,755  -->  00:00:23,020
Let's talk about KeyError.

8

00:00:23,020  -->  00:00:27,750
If we want to check for a particular food item at your theme park,

9

00:00:27,750  -->  00:00:32,650
let's first define the types of food stalls and how many there are of each.

10

00:00:32,650  -->  00:00:37,110
For example, let's say that there's five popcorn and three pretzel stands.

11

00:00:37,110  -->  00:00:41,810
We'll run a function that takes in an argument of check food for us

12

00:00:41,810  -->  00:00:46,835
to check if the type of food stall is available in the theme park. We'll do this.

13

00:00:46,835  -->  00:00:53,420
Like so. We'll create a food Stalls variable and we'll set that equal to this object,

14

00:00:53,420  -->  00:00:55,300
which will be our dictionary,

15

00:00:55,300  -->  00:00:58,680
and we'll say that there's five popcorn and three pretzel.

16

00:00:58,680  -->  00:01:00,260
Now, we'll define a function,

17

00:01:00,260  -->  00:01:05,820
and we'll say Def check food availability.

18

00:01:05,820  -->  00:01:07,780
We'll say check food.

19

00:01:07,780  -->  00:01:11,820
Then we'll try and we'll print food stalls.

20

00:01:11,820  -->  00:01:18,240
We'll then pass it and check SD to check the key of that dictionary based on the index,

21

00:01:18,240  -->  00:01:25,190
and then we will accept a KeyError as e. Then we'll say print.

22

00:01:25,190  -->  00:01:28,460
We'll do an F string, say KeyError.

23

00:01:28,460  -->  00:01:34,510
Occurred. We'll pass in our e with squiggly braces? We'll close it out.

24

00:01:34,510  -->  00:01:37,340
Then if we want to check,

25

00:01:37,340  -->  00:01:39,300
if a certain food is in there,

26

00:01:39,300  -->  00:01:43,735
we'll pass in as an argument into check food churro.

27

00:01:43,735  -->  00:01:50,060
This is for us to check if churro is one of the food stalls that's in your theme park.

28

00:01:50,060  -->  00:01:51,560
If we were to run this code,

29

00:01:51,560  -->  00:01:53,360
what do you think the output will be?

30

00:01:53,360  -->  00:01:55,220
If we run this, let's find out.

31

00:01:55,220  -->  00:01:58,385
We'll see key occurred churro.

32

00:01:58,385  -->  00:02:05,500
That's because churro does not exist in the list of food stalls in this dictionary.

33

00:02:05,500  -->  00:02:07,725
Now, what if we asked about Pretzel?

34

00:02:07,725  -->  00:02:09,240
See that example.

35

00:02:09,240  -->  00:02:11,670
If we were to pass in Pretzel,

36

00:02:11,670  -->  00:02:13,090
instead of churro,

37

00:02:13,090  -->  00:02:14,930
what do you think the output of this will be?

38

00:02:14,930  -->  00:02:19,690
We'll see a three printed out telling us that there are three pretzel stands

39

00:02:19,690  -->  00:02:24,290
because we are passing in Pretzel to identify the key,

40

00:02:24,290  -->  00:02:29,510
and then this will return the value of what that's set to.

41

00:02:29,510  -->  00:02:33,690
In this case, since churro isn't in the dictionary food stalls,

42

00:02:33,690  -->  00:02:36,370
Python raises that KeyError that we saw,

43

00:02:36,370  -->  00:02:40,260
which is like a guest asking for something that isn't on the menu.

44

00:02:40,260  -->  00:02:44,250
KeyErrors can help us isolate what is and isn't there for

45

00:02:44,250  -->  00:02:46,950
better visibility across a list of items

46

00:02:46,950  -->  00:02:50,190
should someone ask for something that well isn't there.

47

00:02:50,190  -->  00:02:52,790
But if they do ask for something that is there,

48

